Chhatrapati Shivaji Maharaj (1630–1680) was the visionary founder of the Maratha Empire and is celebrated as one of India's greatest warrior-kings. He didn't just fight for territory; he established the concept of "Hindavi Swarajya" (self-rule of the people). 
Here is a concise overview of his life, military genius, and governance.
1. Early Life and Vision
Born in the hill fort of Shivneri to Shahaji Bhonsle and Jijabai, Shivaji was raised with a deep sense of justice and independence. While his father served the Adilshahi Sultanate, Shivaji’s mother and his mentor, Dadoji Konddeo, instilled in him the dream of a free kingdom. 
First Conquest: At just 16, he captured Torna Fort, marking the beginning of his campaign.
Fortification Strategy: He eventually controlled over 300 forts, recognizing that in the rugged terrain of Maharashtra, forts were the "mother of the kingdom." 
2. Iconic Military Encounters
Shivaji was a master of Ganimi Kava (Guerrilla Warfare), using the terrain and speed to defeat much larger imperial armies. 
Event 	Opponent	Outcome
Battle of Pratapgad (1569)	Afzal Khan (Adilshahi)	Shivaji famously killed the giant general with "tiger claws" (Wagh Nakh) after an attempted ambush.
Raid on Shaista Khan (1663)	Mughal Empire	Shivaji infiltrated the Mughal camp in Pune and wounded the General, humiliating the Mughal forces.
Escape from Agra (1666)	Emperor Aurangzeb	After being house-arrested by Aurangzeb, Shivaji and his son Sambhaji escaped hidden in large sweet baskets.
3. The Coronation (1674)
In a defiant move against the Mughals and the Deccan Sultanates, Shivaji was formally crowned as Chhatrapati (Paramount Sovereign) at Raigad Fort. This sent a message that he was not a mere vassal or chieftain, but a King of a sovereign state. 
4. Governance and Legacy
Shivaji Maharaj is remembered as much for his administration as his battles. He was centuries ahead of his time in several ways: 
Father of Indian Navy: He built a powerful coastal navy and sea forts like Sindhudurg to protect the Konkan coast from foreign traders and pirates.
Ashta Pradhan Mandal: He created a council of eight ministers to manage specialized departments of the state.
Social Justice: He was a champion for the common man, strictly forbidding the harassment of women during war and ensuring farmers were not over-taxed.
Religious Tolerance: While he was a proud Hindu, his army and administration included many high-ranking Muslims, and he ordered his soldiers to protect mosques and the Quran. 
